file: /cmds/mortal/friend.c
keywords: friends, wall
aliases:
short: Managing your Friend List
header: Friends Management
syntax: friend <optional arguments>

Use the 'friend' command to manage your friend list and the privacy
settings of your alternate characters.

Use this command in conjuntion with others listed at the end of this file.

Just like the name implies, your friends list is where you keep track of
your various friends and acquaintances here on 3-Kingdoms.  What does the
friends list offer that the older mywho doesn't?

  * Maintain a single list across all your characters
  * Members of your friends list are tied to the human, not the
    character - forget having to remember who all those alts belong to
  * Only allow the the alts you want to be visible - keep your secret
    characters secret
  * The same old functionality as mywho, to boot! (see stalking below)
  * Sync your current mywho list as stalkees
  * Post messages to your wall for others to see (help wall for details)

When you add a friend, they have to accept your friend request.
You will both show up on one another's lists, and will be able to see
any visible alternate characters of each others.

* See: friend hide/unhide below for details on alt visibility.

When you stalk someone, you add them to your list without their
knowledge.  You do not see any information about their other characters,
nor do you get other privileges of being their friend (like being able
to write on their wall, for instance).

    IMPORTANT: You will have 50 available spaces in your list for
    friends, and 50 available spaces for stalkees.

    See 'vaf friends' for information on how to increase the limit
    of your friends list.  Your stalkee limit will always be 50,
    regardless of any VAF perks.

    If you have previous mywho vaf selections, you can convert
    them to friends credits by typing 'vaf mywho2friends'.

friend <character/nickname>
  View details about a friend (their characters, etc), and/or any
  stalkees you have under the name.

friend add <character> <nickname>
  Send a request to someone, with <nickname> being the name you
  tie to the human and all of their characters.  Nicknames you supply will
  always be forced into lowercase.
  (example: friend add gothbunny bob)

  They will have 5 minutes to accept the request before it expires.
  If they accept in time, you become mutual friends!

friend remove <nickname>
  Sever your friendship with someone permanently.  You are of course
  free to reconnect with them again whenever you like.

friend rename <oldnickname> <newnickname>
  Change someone's nickname on your friends list.

friend stalk <character> <nickname>
  Unlike adding someone as a friend, the person you stalk will not see
  you add them to this list.  In turn, you will not be able to see what
  other characters this person has.  This is essentially the same
  functionality as mywho.

friend unstalk <character>
  Remove this character from your list of stalkees.

friend mywhosync
  Add everybody from your mywho list as stalkees.

friend hidden
  View which characters are hidden and which are visible.
  This will also show you which characters have private walls and 
  public walls.

friend hide <character>
  Hide one of your characters from being revealed as your alt.

friend unhide <character>
  Reveal one of your hidden characters as your alt.


