file: /help/CMDS/mudlag
keywords: mortal, 
aliases: lag
short: Current driver load information
header: Command: Mudlag

   SYNTAX:  mudlag

The 'mudlag' command provides all sorts of useful information on
the status of the internal resources the mud is working with, and
the lag that is being generated by them.

The mudlag report is composed of the following:

Lag Average - The lag average is an objective quantity that
closely correlates with the delay between the time when
a user enters a command and when he gets a response from the
mud (sans any network delays).  The mud is supposed to have a
heart_beat every 2 seconds, but when the driver is under load,
the heart_beat is usually delayed.  The term 'lag' refers to
this delay time in seconds, and the 'lag average' is the average
heart_beat delay in the period during which it is measured.

CPU Usage - This is the percentage of CPU time that the mud
driver process was allotted by the system.  If it's high, the
mud driver is doing a lot of thinking.  If it's low, either
the mud driver just doesn'
t have much to think about or the CPU
is being allotted to some other process on the system and the
driver process is being forced to wait and share.  The latter
case would contribute to lag.

Driver Load - This shows the average number of commands from
users that the driver is processing every second (cmds/s),
and the average number of lines of LPC code that the driver
is compiling every second (lines/s).  The cmds/s varies
depending on the rate at which players are entering commands
and is limited by the rate at which the driver can process
those commands.  The lines/s correlates to the number of new
objects that the driver is loading into memory.  When the
mud is first booted, this number is very high because the
driver has to load every object in anew.  I don't know over
what period of time the averaging for these values is being
done.

Load Average - The first 3 numbers is the system load average.
It is the number of jobs in the run queue averaged over 1, 5
and 15 minutes respectively.  It indicates the level of
utilization of and competition for the CPU and other system
resources.

